{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QZfPqgPsh6Ch8ZtgLt55Ca","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Title Extractor Architecture\n     2→\n     3→## Pipeline Overview\n     4→\n     5→The title extractor (`lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`) takes raw OCR text from recipe photos and identifies recipe titles using a multi-stage pipeline combining structural heuristics and semantic embeddings.\n     6→\n     7→```\n     8→                          RAW OCR TEXT\n     9→                              |\n    10→                    +---------v----------+\n    11→                    |   Split into lines  |\n    12→                    +--------------------+\n    13→                              |\n    14→                    +---------v----------+\n    15→                    |  Skip garbled burst |  findBurstEnd(): discard leading\n    16→                    |  (short OCR noise)  |  short lines with bad vowel ratios\n    17→                    +--------------------+\n    18→                              |\n    19→                    +---------v----------+\n    20→                    |  Pre-merge          |  Lines starting with /&+:( are\n    21→                    |  continuation lines |  joined to preceding line\n    22→                    +--------------------+    e.g. \"SAFFRON BUNS\" + \"/ VARIATION\"\n    23→                              |               -> \"SAFFRON BUNS / VARIATION\"\n    24→                    +---------v----------+\n    25→                    |  Generate candidates|  For each line: single, 2-line join,\n    26→                    |  (single + joins)   |  3-line join. Dedup by normalized text.\n    27→                    +--------------------+\n    28→                              |\n    29→                    +---------v----------+\n    30→                    |  Hard filters       |  9 independent checks per candidate\n    31→                    |  (reject non-titles)|  (see detail below)\n    32→                    +--------------------+\n    33→                              |\n    34→                    +---------v----------+\n    35→                    |  Cap at 25          |  Prefer ALL_CAPS + short candidates\n    36→                    |  (pre-filter)       |  to limit embedding API calls\n    37→                    +--------------------+\n    38→                              |\n    39→              ================v=================\n    40→              |     EMBEDDING SCORING            |\n    41→              |                                  |\n    42→              |  +---------v----------+          |\n    43→              |  | Pass 1: rawScore   |          |\n    44→              |  | titleSim - max(    |          |\n    45→              |  |  headerSim,        |          |\n    46→              |  |  noiseSim)         |          |\n    47→              |  +--------------------+          |\n    48→              |            |                     |\n    49→              |  +---------v----------+          |\n    50→              |  | Structural heading  |         |\n    51→              |  | selection           |         |\n    52→              |  | (best ALL_CAPS by   |         |\n    53→              |  |  embedding quality) |         |\n    54→              |  +--------------------+          |\n    55→              |            |                     |\n    56→              |  +---------v----------+          |\n    57→              |  | OCR truncation      |         |\n    58→              |  | penalty (-1.0)      |         |\n    59→              |  | \"FRON\" vs \"SAFFRON\" |         |\n    60→              |  +--------------------+          |\n    61→              |            |                     |\n    62→              |  +---------v----------+          |\n    63→              |  | Pass 2: bonuses     |         |\n    64→              |  | position * 1.12     |         |\n    65→              |  | ALL_CAPS + 0.08     |         |\n    66→              |  | structural + 0.10   |         |\n    67→              |  +--------------------+          |\n    68→              |                                  |\n    69→              ==================================+\n    70→                              |\n    71→                    +---------v----------+\n    72→                    |  Bilingual          |  Suppress ALL_CAPS translation at\n    73→                    |  detection          |  pos 1-2 if cosine > 0.4 with\n    74→                    |  (pre-threshold)    |  mixed-case title at pos 0\n    75→                    +--------------------+\n    76→                              |\n    77→                    +---------v----------+\n    78→                    |  Threshold filter   |  max(0.08, bestThresholdScore * 0.7)\n    79→                    |                     |  Empty-pool fallback: if nothing\n    80→                    |                     |  survives, take best positional\n    81→                    +--------------------+\n    82→                              |\n    83→                    +---------v----------+\n    84→                    |  Post-threshold     |\n    85→                    |  cleanup            |\n    86→                    |  - prefix removal   |  Remove \"ARAYES\" when \"ARAYES SHRAK\" present\n    87→                    |  - join protection  |  Keep continuation joins, drop fragments\n    88→                    |  - sub-section      |  Remove ALL_CAPS headers followed by\n    89→                    |    removal          |  ingredients when longer parent exists\n    90→                    +--------------------+\n    91→                              |\n    92→                    +---------v----------+\n    93→                    |  Dedup              |  Shorter substring wins\n    94→                    |  (substring-based)  |  \"Pierogi Ruskie\" beats\n    95→                    +--------------------+  \"Pierogi Ruskie 200g maki\"\n    96→                              |\n    97→                    +---------v----------+\n    98→                    |  Multi-title guard  |  2+ ALL_CAPS -> check ingredient gaps\n    99→                    |                     |  1 ALL_CAPS -> highest score wins\n   100→                    |                     |  0 ALL_CAPS -> keep all\n   101→                    +--------------------+\n   102→                              |\n   103→                    +---------v----------+\n   104→                    |  Sort by position,  |\n   105→                    |  cap at 3, join     |\n   106→                    |  with \" + \"         |\n   107→                    +--------------------+\n   108→                              |\n   109→                        EXTRACTED TITLE\n   110→```\n   111→\n   112→## Hard Filters Detail\n   113→\n   114→`passesHardFilters()` applies 9 independent checks. A candidate is rejected if **any** check fails:\n   115→\n   116→| # | Filter | Example rejected |\n   117→|---|--------|-----------------|\n   118→| 1 | Length 3-80 chars | `\"A\"`, very long body text |\n   119→| 2 | Ingredient detection | `\"2 cups flour\"`, `\"100g masla\"`, `\"do smaku\"` |\n   120→| 3 | Leading number | `\"1. Preheat oven\"`, `\"- 2 jajka\"` |\n   121→| 4 | Metadata patterns | `\"SERVES 4\"`, `\"NA 3 PAPRYKI\"`, `\"30 MIN\"` |\n   122→| 5 | OCR garble | Low vowel ratio, lowercase-start, mid-sentence boundary |\n   123→| 6 | Pipe separator | `\"Lato \\| Dania glowne\"` (chapter header) |\n   124→| 7 | Bullet line | `\"- flour\"`, `\"* sugar\"` |\n   125→| 8 | Section label | `\"INGREDIENTS\"`, `\"SKLADNIKI\"`, `\"Przygotowanie\"` |\n   126→| 9 | Non-title single word | `\"the\"`, `\"and\"`, `\"buns\"`, `\"with\"` |\n   127→\n   128→## Scoring Model\n   129→\n   130→Each candidate receives a composite score built from three signals:\n   131→\n   132→```\n   133→rawScore = cosineSim(candidate, TITLE_REF) - max(\n   134→             cosineSim(candidate, HEADER_REF),\n   135→             cosineSim(candidate, NOISE_REF)\n   136→           )\n   137→\n   138→score = rawScore * positionFactor + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus\n   139→```\n   140→\n   141→**Reference embeddings** (cached across calls):\n   142→- `TITLE_REF`: \"recipe name, dish title, name of the food, nazwa przepisu, nazwa dania\"\n   143→- `HEADER_REF`: \"ingredients list, cooking directions, section heading, skladniki, przygotowanie\"\n   144→- `NOISE_REF`: \"page number, table of contents, book footer, garbled text\"\n   145→\n   146→**Bonuses:**\n   147→\n   148→| Bonus | Value | Condition |\n   149→|-------|-------|-----------|\n   150→| Position factor | x1.0 to x1.12 (multiplicative) | Top-half of document, linear decay |\n   151→| ALL_CAPS | +0.08 (additive) | All letters uppercase, >= 4 alpha chars |\n   152→| Structural heading | +0.10 (additive) | Best ALL_CAPS heading by embedding quality |\n   153→\n   154→The `thresholdScore` deliberately excludes the structural bonus to prevent it from inflating the cutoff on multi-recipe pages.\n   155→\n   156→## Key Design Decisions\n   157→\n   158→**Multiplicative position bonus**: Additive position bonuses let garbled early text dominate. Multiplicative amplifies existing quality without creating it.\n   159→\n   160→**Pre-merge over downstream join protection**: Continuation lines (`/&+:`) are merged upstream in `buildCandidates` so the complete title enters the pool as a single candidate. This replaced 5 iterations of fragile downstream join-survival logic.\n   161→\n   162→**Pre-threshold bilingual detection**: Must run before threshold computation. Otherwise the ALL_CAPS translation inflates the threshold beyond the mixed-case primary title's reach (chicken-and-egg problem).\n   163→\n   164→**Shorter-wins dedup**: The dedup rule is intentionally simple (\"shorter substring wins\") because upstream filters (prefix removal, sub-section removal) ensure conflicting shorter fragments are removed before dedup runs. This has been incorrectly \"improved\" 5 times by the automated loop.\n   165→\n   166→## Language Support\n   167→\n   168→The extractor handles both English and Polish recipes:\n   169→- Measurement units: `lyżka`, `szklanka`, `szczypta`, `garsc`\n   170→- Metadata: `NA 3 PAPRYKI`, `DLA 4 OSOB`, `N MIN`, `N GODZ`\n   171→- Section labels: `SKLADNIKI`, `PRZYGOTOWANIE`, `SPOSOB WYKONANIA`\n   172→- OCR garble: Polish vowels (`ąęó`) included in vowel ratio check\n   173→- Common prepositions: `w`, `z` allowed in multi-word garble detection\n   174→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01WXJ8YPSzkXSDBPsZPnb8VX","session_id":"3e646be9-92d4-4481-9255-b1f94813f9c6","uuid":"b7aa7b5c-76cd-439d-b45a-be4735209a11"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019wdakBbw5hYc4bkCi463s1","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 14 Failure Analysis\n     2→\n     3→## Failure 1: LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS\n     4→**Expected:** `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS`\n     5→**Got:** `WITH NIGELLA + SEEDS`\n     6→\n     7→### What happened\n     8→\n     9→The true title is spread across 4 lines in the OCR output:\n    10→```\n    11→LABANEH\n    12→BALLS\n    13→WITH NIGELLA\n    14→SEEDS\n    15→```\n    16→\n    17→The algorithm generates joins up to **3 consecutive lines**, so `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA` (3-line join, position 0) is the longest candidate that captures the start of the title. The full 4-word title `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS` is never in the candidate pool.\n    18→\n    19→With the full title absent, `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA` (3-line) competes against `WITH NIGELLA` (single, position 2) and `WITH NIGELLA SEEDS` (2-line, position 2). All three are structural headings.\n    20→\n    21→The dedup step then eliminates `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA` because it **contains** `WITH NIGELLA` as a substring, and the dedup rule is \"shorter wins\":\n    22→```\n    23→aLower.includes(b.text.toLowerCase()) && b.text.length < a.text.length\n    24→  → removes \"LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA\" (contains \"with nigella\", shorter)\n    25→```\n    26→\n    27→The structural heading prefix-removal guard (`fshLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \")`) does not help here because `WITH NIGELLA` is a **suffix** of `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA`, not a prefix — so it is not stripped before dedup runs.\n    28→\n    29→After dedup, `WITH NIGELLA` and `SEEDS` remain. Both are all-caps. The multi-title guard checks whether the second candidate (`SEEDS`, position 3) is followed by ingredient-like lines — it is not (body text follows) — so `isSubHeader = false` and both survive. Result: `WITH NIGELLA + SEEDS`.\n    30→\n    31→### Root causes\n    32→1. **3-line join ceiling**: a 4-line title is never formed as a candidate.\n    33→2. **Dedup \"shorter wins\" removes valid longer candidate**: `WITH NIGELLA` is a semantic fragment of the title but dedup treats it as more authoritative than the longer join it partially overlaps.\n    34→\n    35→---\n    36→\n    37→## Failure 2: Smażona zielona fasolka\n    38→**Expected:** `Smażona zielona fasolka`\n    39→**Got:** `GREEN BEANS BORKEUM`\n    40→\n    41→### What happened\n    42→\n    43→The OCR text opens with three title variants:\n    44→```\n    45→Line 0: Smażona zielona fasolka   (Polish, mixed-case — true title)\n    46→Line 1: GREEN BEANS BORKEUM       (English + Korean romanization, all-caps)\n    47→Line 2: 그린빈 볶음                 (Korean script — filtered by garbled check)\n    48→```\n    49→\n    50→`Smażona zielona fasolka` is mixed-case (Polish capitalizes only the first word of a title). It never qualifies as a structural heading (`isAllCaps` strips non-ASCII letters, checks only `[a-zA-Z]`, and `Smażona` contains lowercase ASCII letters).\n    51→\n    52→`GREEN BEANS BORKEUM` is all-caps with 3 words each ≥4 letters → it is a structural heading and receives the +0.10 structural bonus, pushing it above the mixed-case Polish title.\n    53→\n    54→The bilingual-title detection is the intended guard: it looks for a mixed-case candidate at position 0 and a nearby all-caps candidate (position 1–2) with cosine similarity > 0.4. If triggered, it suppresses the all-caps candidate from `scoredForThreshold` (and thus from `selected`).\n    55→\n    56→The guard did **not** trigger here. The Polish phrase `Smażona zielona fasolka` and the English+Korean romanization `GREEN BEANS BORKEUM` are semantically equivalent (both mean \"stir-fried green beans\"), but the embedding similarity falls at or below 0.4. Cross-lingual pairs where one language uses completely different script/word roots (Polish vs. Korean romanization) produce lower cosine similarity than bilingual pairs in related European languages.\n    57→\n    58→### Root causes\n    59→1. **Structural bonus overrides true title**: an all-caps secondary title line wins purely because of the +0.10 structural heading bonus, which mixed-case legitimate titles cannot receive.\n    60→2. **Bilingual detection threshold too strict for cross-linguistic pairs**: 0.4 cosine similarity is not reliably met when Polish and Korean romanization embeddings diverge despite shared meaning.\n    61→\n    62→---\n    63→\n    64→## Common Themes\n    65→\n    66→### 1. All-caps structural heading bias is too strong\n    67→The +0.10 structural bonus is enough to flip the winner when the true title is mixed-case (Polish, Italian, etc. capitalization conventions). Recipes in non-English cookbooks often have mixed-case titles on the first line, followed by an all-caps translation or subtitle.\n    68→\n    69→### 2. Candidate pool limited to 3-line joins\n    70→Titles split across 4+ lines cannot be assembled. This is uncommon but occurs here because the OCR broke `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS` into four one-to-two-word lines. The algorithm's pre-merge step only handles lines starting with a continuation character (`/&+:(`), so ordinary word splits across lines are not handled beyond 3.\n    71→\n    72→### 3. Dedup \"shorter wins\" can destroy the best candidate\n    73→The rule is correct for `Pierogi Ruskie` vs `Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki` but breaks down when a shorter overlapping substring is a fragment of the title rather than a more focused title. `WITH NIGELLA` is not a recipe title — it is an OCR fragment — yet it causes the 3-line join to be eliminated.\n    74→\n    75→### 4. Cross-lingual bilingual detection is fragile\n    76→The 0.4 similarity threshold works for closely related language pairs (e.g. Polish + English, French + English) but is too high for pairs like Polish + Korean romanization. The detection also only looks at position 0 (mixed-case) + positions 1–2 (all-caps). If the all-caps translation appears later, or the Polish title is itself at position 1, the guard does not fire.\n    77→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01WXJ8YPSzkXSDBPsZPnb8VX","session_id":"3e646be9-92d4-4481-9255-b1f94813f9c6","uuid":"7f2de1d9-93f9-4c0b-87d5-813b1be1cba1"}
