{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FT1hM4wBJkmVPwfh61WMph","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 15 — Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Overview\n     4→\n     5→Two failures, two distinct root causes, but a shared theme: the algorithm's structural-heading machinery is too rigid for OCR layouts that deviate from the \"single ALL_CAPS line = title\" assumption. The fixes below are targeted but non-trivial — each addresses a design gap rather than patching a symptom.\n     6→\n     7→**Accuracy trajectory:** 14 → 81.8% (regression from 98.1% at iter 13, caused by corpus expansion to 11 recipes exposing pre-existing gaps). The two failures here are new test cases, not regressions.\n     8→\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→## Failure 1: LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS\n    12→\n    13→**Expected:** `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS`\n    14→**Got:** `WITH NIGELLA + SEEDS`\n    15→\n    16→### Root Cause Analysis\n    17→\n    18→Two compounding issues:\n    19→\n    20→1. **3-line join ceiling** — The title spans 4 OCR lines (`LABANEH` / `BALLS` / `WITH NIGELLA` / `SEEDS`). `buildCandidates` generates joins of up to 3 consecutive lines, so the full title is never in the candidate pool. The best candidate covering the start is the 3-line join `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA` (position 0).\n    21→\n    22→2. **Dedup \"shorter wins\" destroys the 3-line join** — `WITH NIGELLA` (single, position 2) is a substring of `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA`. The dedup rule keeps the shorter form, eliminating the only candidate that captures the dish name. After dedup, only `WITH NIGELLA` and `SEEDS` survive, producing `WITH NIGELLA + SEEDS`.\n    23→\n    24→The existing continuation-character pre-merge (`/^[/&+:(]/`) doesn't help because `BALLS`, `WITH NIGELLA`, and `SEEDS` don't start with continuation punctuation — they're just OCR-fragmented words of a single heading.\n    25→\n    26→### Proposed Fix: Short ALL_CAPS Line Merge Pass\n    27→\n    28→Add a **pre-processing pass** in `buildCandidates`, before the existing continuation-character merge, that collapses consecutive short ALL_CAPS lines into single logical lines. The insight: when a recipe page has a sequence of 2+ consecutive ALL_CAPS lines where each line has ≤2 words and ≤25 characters, they are almost certainly fragments of a single heading broken by OCR line detection.\n    29→\n    30→**Algorithm:**\n    31→\n    32→```\n    33→Input lines (after burst skip):\n    34→  LABANEH           (ALL_CAPS, 1 word, 7 chars)\n    35→  BALLS             (ALL_CAPS, 1 word, 5 chars)\n    36→  WITH NIGELLA      (ALL_CAPS, 2 words, 12 chars)\n    37→  SEEDS             (ALL_CAPS, 1 word, 5 chars)\n    38→  Essential to...   (mixed-case, long — breaks the run)\n    39→\n    40→After short-caps merge:\n    41→  LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS   (merged, position 0)\n    42→  Essential to...                     (unchanged)\n    43→```\n    44→\n    45→**Merge criteria for each line in the run:**\n    46→- `isAllCaps(line)` is true\n    47→- `wordCount(line) <= 2`\n    48→- `line.length <= 25`\n    49→- NOT a section label (`isSectionLabel` returns false)\n    50→- NOT a metadata line (`looksLikeMetadata` returns false)\n    51→\n    52→**Run termination:** The run breaks when a line fails any criterion, or is empty, or when the accumulated merged text exceeds 80 characters (the existing `passesHardFilters` length cap).\n    53→\n    54→**Where in the code:** In `buildCandidates`, after the `burstEnd` computation and before the continuation-character pre-merge loop. The merged lines feed into the existing continuation merge and candidate generation unchanged.\n    55→\n    56→**Before:**\n    57→```typescript\n    58→// Pre-merge continuation lines: a line starting with /&+:( ...\n    59→const mergedLines: Array<{ text: string; index: number }> = [];\n    60→for (let i = burstEnd; i < nonEmptyLines.length; i++) {\n    61→```\n    62→\n    63→**After:**\n    64→```typescript\n    65→// Pre-merge consecutive short ALL_CAPS lines (OCR-fragmented headings)\n    66→const capsCoalesced: Array<{ text: string; index: number }> = [];\n    67→let i = burstEnd;\n    68→while (i < nonEmptyLines.length) {\n    69→  const line = nonEmptyLines[i];\n    70→  if (\n    71→    isAllCaps(line.text) &&\n    72→    wordCount(line.text) <= 2 &&\n    73→    line.text.length <= 25 &&\n    74→    !isSectionLabel(line.text) &&\n    75→    !looksLikeMetadata(line.text)\n    76→  ) {\n    77→    // Start a run of short ALL_CAPS lines\n    78→    let merged = line.text;\n    79→    const startIndex = line.index;\n    80→    let j = i + 1;\n    81→    while (j < nonEmptyLines.length) {\n    82→      const next = nonEmptyLines[j];\n    83→      if (\n    84→        isAllCaps(next.text) &&\n    85→        wordCount(next.text) <= 2 &&\n    86→        next.text.length <= 25 &&\n    87→        !isSectionLabel(next.text) &&\n    88→        !looksLikeMetadata(next.text) &&\n    89→        (merged + \" \" + next.text).length <= 80\n    90→      ) {\n    91→        merged += \" \" + next.text;\n    92→        j++;\n    93→      } else {\n    94→        break;\n    95→      }\n    96→    }\n    97→    if (j > i + 1) {\n    98→      // Merged 2+ lines into one\n    99→      capsCoalesced.push({ text: merged, index: startIndex });\n   100→      i = j;\n   101→      continue;\n   102→    }\n   103→  }\n   104→  capsCoalesced.push(line);\n   105→  i++;\n   106→}\n   107→\n   108→// Pre-merge continuation lines: a line starting with /&+:( ...\n   109→const mergedLines: Array<{ text: string; index: number }> = [];\n   110→for (let k = 0; k < capsCoalesced.length; k++) {\n   111→  // (rest of existing logic, but iterating over capsCoalesced instead of nonEmptyLines starting at burstEnd)\n   112→```\n   113→\n   114→**Why this works:**\n   115→- `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS` enters the pool as a single candidate at position 0.\n   116→- It qualifies as a structural heading (ALL_CAPS, 5 significant words ≥4 letters).\n   117→- No substring fragment can beat it in dedup because the full title is a single candidate now.\n   118→- The 3-line join ceiling becomes irrelevant for this case — the problem is solved at the source.\n   119→\n   120→**Safety considerations:**\n   121→- The merge only fires for ALL_CAPS short lines. Mixed-case lines (which could be separate paragraphs) are never merged.\n   122→- Section labels like `INGREDIENTS` or `SKŁADNIKI` break the run, preventing \"TITLE INGREDIENTS NEXT_TITLE\" merges.\n   123→- The 80-char cap matches `passesHardFilters` and prevents runaway merges of many short lines.\n   124→- Existing tests: `ARAYES\\nSHRAK` (2 short ALL_CAPS lines) should still work — they'll be merged into `ARAYES SHRAK` even earlier, which is the correct result. The `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS` + `FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` test has multi-word (>2 word) lines and body text between them, so no merge fires.\n   125→\n   126→**Potential concern — CHLEBEK test:**\n   127→```\n   128→CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM    (5 words — too many for merge)\n   129→WARZYWA I BOCZEK                  (3 words — too many for merge)\n   130→```\n   131→Both lines have >2 words, so they don't trigger the short-caps merge. Safe.\n   132→\n   133→---\n   134→\n   135→## Failure 2: Smażona zielona fasolka\n   136→\n   137→**Expected:** `Smażona zielona fasolka`\n   138→**Got:** `GREEN BEANS BORKEUM`\n   139→\n   140→### Root Cause Analysis\n   141→\n   142→Two compounding issues:\n   143→\n   144→1. **Structural bonus inaccessible to mixed-case titles** — `Smażona zielona fasolka` is the correct title at position 0 (mixed-case, Polish convention). `GREEN BEANS BORKEUM` at position 1 (ALL_CAPS, English+Korean romanization) receives the +0.08 ALL_CAPS bonus and +0.10 structural heading bonus, pushing it above the Polish title.\n   145→\n   146→2. **Bilingual detection threshold too strict** — The guard at lines 451-472 checks whether the position-0 mixed-case candidate and a nearby ALL_CAPS candidate have cosine similarity > 0.4. For Polish ↔ Korean romanization (\"BORKEUM\" = 볶음 = stir-fry), MiniLM embeddings can't reliably achieve 0.4 because the word roots are completely unrelated across these language families.\n   147→\n   148→### Proposed Fix: Position-Based Bilingual Layout Detection\n   149→\n   150→Replace the embedding-similarity bilingual guard with a **layout-based heuristic** that doesn't depend on cross-lingual semantic similarity at all. The key insight: in multilingual cookbooks, the layout is deterministic:\n   151→\n   152→```\n   153→Line 0: Primary title (native language, often mixed-case)\n   154→Line 1: Translation / romanization (often ALL_CAPS)\n   155→Line 2: Second script / additional translation (often filtered by garbled check)\n   156→```\n   157→\n   158→When this layout is detected, the position-0 candidate should be strongly preferred regardless of embedding similarity between the two title forms.\n   159→\n   160→**New heuristic — `isBilingualHeader`:**\n   161→\n   162→The existing bilingual guard (lines 451-472) should be expanded with a second, independent trigger condition:\n   163→\n   164→```\n   165→Trigger condition (NEW — layout-based, no embedding similarity required):\n   166→  1. There exists a mixed-case candidate at position 0 with wordCount ≥ 2\n   167→  2. There exists an ALL_CAPS candidate at position 1 or 2 with wordCount ≥ 2\n   168→  3. The mixed-case candidate at position 0 does NOT look like a section label\n   169→  4. The ALL_CAPS candidate is NOT a structural section label\n   170→  5. The two candidates share NO words in common (cross-lingual indicator —\n   171→     same-language titles like \"Pierogi Ruskie\" / \"PIEROGI RUSKIE\" would share words)\n   172→```\n   173→\n   174→When triggered, suppress the ALL_CAPS candidate from `scoredForThreshold` (same as current bilingual guard behavior), preventing its bonuses from inflating the threshold and ensuring the mixed-case position-0 title wins.\n   175→\n   176→**Before (existing guard):**\n   177→```typescript\n   178→let scoredForThreshold = scored;\n   179→const prePos0 = scored.find((s) => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text));\n   180→if (prePos0) {\n   181→  const nearbyAllCaps = scored.filter(\n   182→    (s) => isAllCaps(s.text) && s.position >= 1 && s.position <= 2\n   183→  );\n   184→  const pos0Embedding = rawScored.find((r) => r.text === prePos0.text)?.embedding;\n   185→  if (pos0Embedding && nearbyAllCaps.length > 0) {\n   186→    const translationCandidates = nearbyAllCaps.filter((cap) => {\n   187→      const capEmbedding = rawScored.find((r) => r.text === cap.text)?.embedding;\n   188→      if (!capEmbedding) return false;\n   189→      return cosineSimilarity(pos0Embedding, capEmbedding) > 0.4;\n   190→    });\n   191→    // ... suppress translationCandidates\n   192→  }\n   193→}\n   194→```\n   195→\n   196→**After (layout-based fallback added):**\n   197→```typescript\n   198→let scoredForThreshold = scored;\n   199→const prePos0 = scored.find((s) => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text));\n   200→if (prePos0) {\n   201→  const nearbyAllCaps = scored.filter(\n   202→    (s) => isAllCaps(s.text) && s.position >= 1 && s.position <= 2\n   203→      && s.origin === \"single\"  // only single-line ALL_CAPS, not joins\n   204→  );\n   205→  const pos0Embedding = rawScored.find((r) => r.text === prePos0.text)?.embedding;\n   206→\n   207→  let translationCandidates: typeof nearbyAllCaps = [];\n   208→\n   209→  // Method 1: embedding similarity (existing — works for related languages)\n   210→  if (pos0Embedding && nearbyAllCaps.length > 0) {\n   211→    translationCandidates = nearbyAllCaps.filter((cap) => {\n   212→      const capEmbedding = rawScored.find((r) => r.text === cap.text)?.embedding;\n   213→      if (!capEmbedding) return false;\n   214→      return cosineSimilarity(pos0Embedding, capEmbedding) > 0.4;\n   215→    });\n   216→  }\n   217→\n   218→  // Method 2: layout-based detection (NEW — works for distant languages)\n   219→  // If embedding similarity didn't find translations, check layout:\n   220→  // mixed-case ≥2 words at pos 0 + ALL_CAPS ≥2 words at pos 1-2 sharing no words\n   221→  if (translationCandidates.length === 0 && wordCount(prePos0.text) >= 2) {\n   222→    const pos0Words = new Set(\n   223→      prePos0.text.toLowerCase().split(/\\s+/).filter(w => w.length > 2)\n   224→    );\n   225→    translationCandidates = nearbyAllCaps.filter((cap) => {\n   226→      if (wordCount(cap.text) < 2) return false;\n   227→      const capWords = cap.text.toLowerCase().split(/\\s+/).filter(w => w.length > 2);\n   228→      // No significant words in common → likely different languages\n   229→      const hasCommonWord = capWords.some(w => pos0Words.has(w));\n   230→      return !hasCommonWord;\n   231→    });\n   232→  }\n   233→\n   234→  if (translationCandidates.length > 0) {\n   235→    // (existing suppression logic, unchanged)\n   236→    scoredForThreshold = scored.filter((s) => {\n   237→      const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n   238→      return !translationCandidates.some((t) => sLower.startsWith(t.text.toLowerCase()));\n   239→    });\n   240→  }\n   241→}\n   242→```\n   243→\n   244→**Why this works for `Smażona zielona fasolka`:**\n   245→- Position 0: `Smażona zielona fasolka` (mixed-case, 3 words)\n   246→- Position 1: `GREEN BEANS BORKEUM` (ALL_CAPS, 3 words, single-line)\n   247→- No words in common (Polish vs English+Korean)\n   248→- Layout trigger fires → `GREEN BEANS BORKEUM` suppressed from threshold\n   249→- `Smażona zielona fasolka` wins on position\n   250→\n   251→**Why this is safe for existing tests:**\n   252→\n   253→- **Faszerowana papryka test:** Position 0 = `Faszerowana papryka` (mixed-case), Position 1 = `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM` (ALL_CAPS). Words: {faszerowana, papryka} vs {paprika, gyeran-jjim}. \"papryka\" vs \"paprika\" — these don't match exactly as strings. The layout guard fires and suppresses the ALL_CAPS line, which is the **already correct** behavior (previously achieved via embedding similarity). No regression.\n   254→\n   255→- **CHOCOLATE CAKE test:** `CHOCOLATE CAKE` is at position 0 and is itself ALL_CAPS, so `prePos0` (looking for mixed-case at position 0) is null. Guard doesn't fire. Safe.\n   256→\n   257→- **ARAYES SHRAK test:** Both lines are ALL_CAPS. No mixed-case at position 0. Guard doesn't fire. Safe.\n   258→\n   259→- **FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS test:** Both are ALL_CAPS. No mixed-case at position 0. Guard doesn't fire. Safe.\n   260→\n   261→- **CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM test:** ALL_CAPS at position 0. No mixed-case at position 0. Guard doesn't fire. Safe.\n   262→\n   263→- **Pierogi Ruskie test:** Position 0 = `Składniki` (section label, filtered by hard filters). Position 1 = `Pierogi Ruskie`. There's no mixed-case candidate at position 0 that passes filters. Guard doesn't fire. Safe.\n   264→\n   265→**Potential concern — false positives on single-language pages:**\n   266→Could a page have a mixed-case title at line 0 and a different ALL_CAPS recipe title at line 1? This would be unusual layout — recipe books don't typically put two different recipe titles on consecutive lines in the same language. The \"no words in common\" check provides additional safety: if the titles are in the same language, they'd likely share at least a preposition or article. But to be extra safe, we restrict this to `origin === \"single\"` for the ALL_CAPS candidates (not joins) since joins of disparate content could spuriously match.\n   267→\n   268→---\n   269→\n   270→## Summary of Changes\n   271→\n   272→| Change | Files | Risk | Impact |\n   273→|--------|-------|------|--------|\n   274→| Short ALL_CAPS line merge pass | `title-extractor.ts` (~30 lines in `buildCandidates`) | Low — only fires on ≤2 word ALL_CAPS lines | Fixes LABANEH; enables future 4+ line titles |\n   275→| Layout-based bilingual detection | `title-extractor.ts` (~15 lines in bilingual guard) | Low — fallback, only fires when embedding guard doesn't | Fixes Smażona zielona fasolka; covers all language pairs |\n   276→\n   277→**Neither change modifies:**\n   278→- The dedup logic (explicitly warned not to change)\n   279→- The structural heading selection\n   280→- The scoring formula\n   281→- The multi-title guard\n   282→- Any hard filters\n   283→\n   284→**Expected accuracy:** 11/11 (100%) — both failures addressed without regressions to existing 9 passing cases.\n   285→\n   286→---\n   287→\n   288→## Testing Plan\n   289→\n   290→### New unit tests needed:\n   291→\n   292→1. **4-line ALL_CAPS title merge:** Input with `LABANEH\\nBALLS\\nWITH NIGELLA\\nSEEDS\\n<body text>`. Expected: `LABANEH BALLS WITH NIGELLA SEEDS`.\n   293→\n   294→2. **Short-caps merge doesn't merge across section labels:** Input with `WORD ONE\\nINGREDIENTS\\nWORD TWO`. Expected: merge does NOT happen (INGREDIENTS breaks the run).\n   295→\n   296→3. **Short-caps merge respects word-count limit:** Input with `THREE WORD LINE\\nANOTHER LINE`. Expected: no merge (first line has 3 words, exceeds ≤2 limit).\n   297→\n   298→4. **Layout bilingual detection with no shared words:** Input with `Mixed Case Title\\nALL CAPS DIFFERENT\\n<body>`. Expected: mixed-case title wins.\n   299→\n   300→5. **Layout bilingual detection skipped when words overlap:** Input with `Apple Pie Recipe\\nAPPLE PIE DELUXE\\n<body>`. Expected: normal scoring (shared words \"apple\", \"pie\" prevent bilingual suppression).\n   301→\n   302→### Regression tests (existing, must still pass):\n   303→- All 15 existing `extractTitleWithEmbeddings` tests in `title-extractor.test.ts`\n   304→- Full corpus run via `title-loop.py` against all 11 input files\n   305→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01WXJ8YPSzkXSDBPsZPnb8VX","session_id":"3e646be9-92d4-4481-9255-b1f94813f9c6","uuid":"9d82c831-aabf-4de2-9f51-24107b499dcd"}
