{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01JEC8cGz44tKoLiSTaXFoLE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. Let me analyze the current failure and propose fixes.\n\nThe single failure is:\n- **File:** `Faszerowana papryka.real.txt`\n- **Expected:** `Faszerowana papryka`\n- **Got:** `WARZYWA`\n\nRoot causes from the feedback:\n1. `SECTION_LABELS` doesn't include Polish chapter/category labels like \"WARZYWA\" (vegetables), \"MIĘSO\" (meat), etc.\n2. Multi-title guard's \"single ALL_CAPS → collapse to highest score\" is positionally blind\n3. `allCapsBonus` is unconditional for single-word ALL_CAPS\n\n\n4. The most direct solution is to add common Polish food category words to `SECTION_LABELS` — warzywa, mięso, ryby, desery, zupy, sałatki, napoje, pieczywo, makarony — so they're recognized as section headers rather than titles. I should also make the multi-title guard position-aware by checking if an ALL_CAPS candidate appears in the last portion of the document, which would indicate it's a section label rather than the actual recipe title.\n\nI could also reduce the ALL_CAPS bonus for single-word terms since those are much more likely to be category labels. Combining all three approaches seems most robust — expanding the blocklist is the safest change, the position check is moderately safe, and reducing the single-word bonus carries some regression risk but seems unlikely given the test cases. words though.\n\nLet me also think about whether there's a more fundamental approach. The feedback hints at it: \"ALL_CAPS bonus system designed to prefer recipe titles inadvertently elevates vocabulary-category labels.\"\n\nOne insight: category/chapter labels tend to be generic food-category words, while recipe titles tend to be specific dish names. But detecting this difference reliably without a language model is hard.\n\nAnother insight: category labels in recipe books typically appear at the very end or very beginning of a page, separated from recipe content. A label that appears AFTER ingredients and instructions is almost certainly a footer/next-section marker.\n\nI think the right approach is a combination:\n1. **Expand SECTION_LABELS** — catches the known cases\n2. **Position-aware single-ALL_CAPS guard** — catches unknown cases structurally\n3. **Reduce allCapsBonus for single-word candidates** — reduces the score inflation\n\nNow let me draft the improvement plan.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1745,"cache_read_input_tokens":35225,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1745},"output_tokens":13,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3e646be9-92d4-4481-9255-b1f94813f9c6","uuid":"baa97cde-9522-44b9-b357-dded4094c163"}
